      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nThere is an old saying: “Looks can be deceiving,” and sometimes these misunderstandings occur because we don't pay attention to details or because we assume there is only one possible answer, without considering all contexts.\n\nLet's begin with a practical example. Observe **Figure 1**, displayed at the National Museum of Anthropology - Mexico (<htcite0>):",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "0be2ea18-ab78-4cb1-b3be-1ff0ba4ade95",
                     "text": "Museo Nacional de Antropologia",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"imgOaxaca\" src=\"\" class=\"imgcenter\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgOaxaca', '0%')\" style=\"width: 30%\" /><b>Figure 1</b>: Writing present at the National Museum of Anthropology - Mexico (<htcite0>). Photo taken on <htdate0>, during a visit to the museum.</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "0be2ea18-ab78-4cb1-b3be-1ff0ba4ade95",
                     "text": "Museo Nacional de Antropologia",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2016",
                     "month": "10",
                     "day": "22"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: “It is undoubtedly Mayan.” Really?</b><br /><br />Have you ever heard of “Mayan numbers”?<br /><br />If so, is <b>Figure 1</b> an example of them?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "In the texts of *History Tracers*, as in the previous text (<htcite0>), we have avoided using the expression “Mayan numbers,” since these numbers were not used only by the Maya in Mesoamerica. In **Figure 1**, for example, we have a stela from Oaxaca, a Mixtec city (<htcite1>), made around <htdate0> — according to the information displayed next to the image in the museum (<htcite2>).\n\nSimilarly, confusion also occurs with the different abacuses, which is why we study them separately.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "339c7ff5-8365-49bb-a1cd-ad5a13d5fd86",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Building to count (Soroban, 算盤)",
